Groundnut
Groundnut (Arachis hypogaea L.) is an important oilseed crop known for its oil content of 44-50%, used in various industries including soap making, cosmetics, and as feed for livestock.<SEP>Groundnut is a crop that requires specific pest and disease management strategies for optimal growth and yield.

Gujarat
Gujarat is one of the four states in India where groundnut production is concentrated.

Andhra Pradesh
Andhra Pradesh is one of the four states in India where groundnut production is concentrated.

Tamil Nadu
Tamil Nadu is one of the four states in India where groundnut production is concentrated.

Karnataka
Karnataka is one of the four states in India where groundnut production is concentrated.

Orissa
Orissa is mentioned as a state with irrigated areas suitable for groundnut cultivation.

Heptachlor
Heptachlor is a chemical used against white grubs in groundnut cultivation.

Chlordane
Chlordane is a chemical used against white grubs in groundnut cultivation.

Rhizobium
Rhizobium is a culture beneficial for increasing nodulation and nitrogen fixation in groundnut plants.

Lasso
Lasso is a type of weedicide used for effective weed control in groundnut cultivation.<SEP>Lasso is a weedicide used for controlling weeds in groundnut cultivation.

Tok-E-25
Tok-E-25 is a weedicide that can be mixed with water for pre-emergence spraying to control weeds in soil.<SEP>Tok-E-25 is a weedicide used for controlling weeds in groundnut cultivation.

Kharif Crop
Kharif crop refers to crops grown during the Indian monsoon season, typically sown in May-June and requiring substantive rainfall. Groundnut is primarily raised as a kharif crop.

May-June
May-June is the time period during which groundnut is typically sown as a kharif crop and is tied to the onset of monsoon rains.

Irrigated Crop
Irrigated crop refers to crops that are watered through irrigation systems rather than relying solely on rainfall. Groundnut is grown as an irrigated crop in limited extents during specific months.

Artificial Fibre
Artificial fibre is a material that can be made from by-products of groundnut, specifically the cake left after oil extraction.

Weeds
Weeds refer to unwanted plants that grow in the fields and compete with groundnut for resources, thus requiring management such as hand-weeding or chemical weed control.

White Grubs
White grubs are pests affecting groundnut cultivation, which damage the crops by feeding on the roots and stems.

Pest Leaf-miner
Pest Leaf-miner is a pest affecting plants by mining and folding leaves, active during July to December.

Groundnut Aphid
Groundnut aphid is a pest that acts as a vector for virus diseases affecting groundnuts.

White Grub
White grub is a pest that emerges after monsoon and feeds on plant roots, leading to plant death.

Root Rot
Root rot is a disease characterized by reddish-brown discoloration and leads to plant collapse.

Tikka Disease
Tikka disease or leaf spot is characterized by dark spots on leaves, leading to premature leaf shedding.

Bunchy Top
Bunchy top is a disease that reduces leaf and internode sizes and can cause partial sterility in plants.

Agrosan GN
Agrosan GN is a treatment used for seeds to manage diseases in crops.

Ceresan
Ceresan is a seed treatment used to control various plant diseases.

Thiram
Thiram is another agent used for treating seeds against diseases.

Brestan
Brestan is a fungicide used for controlling Tikka disease in crops.

Bordeaux Mixture
Bordeaux mixture is a combination used for spraying to manage leaf spot diseases.

Ziram
Ziram is a fungicide applied to control disease in crops, particularly effective against Tikka disease.

Zineb
Zineb is a chemical used to help control diseases in plants like Tikka disease.

Maneb
Maneb is a fungicide utilized in the management of crop diseases.

Harvesting
Harvesting involves techniques for collecting groundnut crops after maturity indicators are present.<SEP>Harvesting is the process of gathering mature soyabean crops using specific methods and indicators of readiness.<SEP>Harvesting refers to the process of collecting mature sugarcane, which is usually coordinated over a 150-day period starting in November.

Semi-spreading varieties
Semi-spreading varieties of groundnuts are harvested by hand pulling when soil conditions are ideal.

Spreading types
Spreading types of groundnuts are harvested using digging or ploughing methods.

Carbaryl
Carbaryl is a pesticide used to control pests such as the Leaf-miner in crops.

Dimethoate
Dimethoate is a pesticide utilized to control pests like the Groundnut aphid to protect crops.

Phosphamidon
Phosphamidon is a chemical used to manage pest infestations in agricultural settings.

Monocroptophos
Monocroptophos is an insecticide suggested for controlling the Groundnut aphid.

Methyl-demeton
Methyl-demeton is used in agriculture to manage pest populations such as the Groundnut aphid.

Soyabean
Soyabean is a crop characterized by specific ecological requirements and agricultural practices for optimal growth and yield.

Kharif Season
Kharif season refers to one of the cropping seasons suitable for sowing soyabean, typically from late June to early July.

Spring Sowing
Spring sowing is another cropping time for soyabean, occurring between February 15 and March 15.

Monetta
Monetta is one of the varieties of soyabean mentioned that can be cultivated.

M.A.C.S.-13
M.A.C.S.-13 is a variety of soyabean suitable for cultivation.

M.A.C.S.-57
M.A.C.S.-57 is another variety of soyabean specified for planting.

M.A.C.S.-58
M.A.C.S.-58 is one of the varieties of soyabean that can be grown.

M.A.C.S-124
M.A.C.S-124 is a designated variety of soyabean for cultivation.

P.K. 472
P.K. 472 is a soyabean variety recommended for planting.

J.S.-80-21
J.S.-80-21 is a variety of soyabean that can be cultivated.

J.S. 335
J.S. 335 is specified as a variety of soyabean for cultivation purposes.

Rhizobium Culture
Rhizobium culture is a treatment used for soyabean seeds to enhance nitrogen fixation.

Fertilizers
Fertilizers are substances applied to soyabean crops to ensure adequate nutrition, particularly nitrogen and phosphorus.<SEP>Fertilizers play a crucial role in sugarcane cultivation, with specific nutrient recommendations based on the planting season and growing conditions.

Water Requirement
Water requirement outlines the irrigation needs for soyabean, especially critical during specific growth stages.

Cultivation Practices
Cultivation practices encompass the techniques and methods involved in planting and caring for the soyabean crop.

Crop Rotation and Inter Cropping
Crop rotation and inter cropping involve planting soyabean with other crops like maize and cotton to enhance growth.

Sandy Loam
Sandy loam is described as the best soil type for soyabean cultivation, having good organic matter content.

Weeding
Weeding is a recommended practice for maintaining the crop, specifically mentioned for the soyabean cultivation process.

Hoeing
Hoeing is mentioned as a method used in conjunction with weeding to contribute to the care of soyabean crops.

Herbicides
Herbicides, such as Toke 25, are utilized for controlling weeds in soyabean cultivation before sowing.

Nitrogen Requirement
Nitrogen requirement refers to the significant need for nitrogen for healthy soyabean growth, exceeding what is fixed by its roots alone.

Sign of Maturity
Signs of maturity for soyabean include the dropping of leaves, yellowing of leaves, and a moisture content of 15% in seeds.

Average Yield
Average yield for soyabean is mentioned as 25g/ha, providing insight into the productivity of this crop.

Sugarcane
Sugarcane is a crop requiring specific agricultural practices such as irrigation, hoeing, and protection from pests and diseases for optimal yield.<SEP>Sugarcane is the main source of sugar in India, recognized as a vital cash crop cultivated over extensive areas, dependent on various climatic and soil conditions.<SEP>Sugarcane is the primary crop being harvested, analyzed, and monitored for maturity, yield, and processing quality.

India
India is the world's largest consumer and the second largest producer of sugar, significant for its extensive sugarcane cultivation involving millions of farmers.

Brazil
Brazil is the largest producer of sugar globally, surpassing India in production volume.

Farmers
Approximately 2.8 lakh farmers cultivate sugarcane in India, relying significantly on the sugar industry for their livelihoods.<SEP>Farmers are the individuals who supply sugarcane after receiving cutting orders from the factory authorities, participating actively in the harvesting process.

Sugar Industry
The sugar industry in India supports over 11 crore people, encompassing both direct and indirect dependence on sugarcane cultivation and processing.

Climate Requirements
Sugarcane requires warm humid conditions with specific temperature and rainfall to thrive, avoiding extremes that can hinder growth.

Soil Requirements
Sugarcane prefers medium heavy soils but can adapt to lighter or heavier soils given proper irrigation and drainage facilitating growth.

Varieties of Sugarcane
Various varieties of sugarcane are mentioned, including CO – 419, CO – 740, and CO.M – 7125, each suited to specific cultivation conditions.

Irrigation
Irrigation involves the controlled application of water to the field to ensure optimal growing conditions for crops like sugarcane.<SEP>Irrigation practices are essential for sugarcane, with specific water requirements at varying growth stages to ensure optimal production.

Intercultural Operations
Intercultural operations such as mulching, hoeing, and tying of cane are necessary practices to enhance growth and protect crops in the field.

Sugarcane Productivity
Sugarcane productivity in India is around 67 t/ha, indicating the yield per hectare that is significant for agricultural performance.

Cultivation Area
Sugarcane is cultivated in an area of 4.4 lakh acres in India, impacting the structure of the agricultural landscape.

Annual Production
India's annual sugarcane production reaches 170 M.T., highlighting its importance in the sugar industry.

Seed Treatment
Seed treatment is a crucial process for better germination and growth of sugarcane, involving various chemical treatments.

Sowing Seasons
Planting of sugarcane is done in three specific seasons: suru (January-February), adsali (July-August), and pre-seasonal (October-November).

Water Logging
Water logging during germination is detrimental as it can lead to rotting of sugarcane setts, a critical consideration in irrigation.

Intercultural Operations Techniques
Techniques such as hoeing, earthing-up, and tying of canes are essential intercultural operations that impact sugarcane cultivation.

Moisture Control
Moisture control through practices like mulching is important to decrease evaporation and improve sugarcane yield.

Termites
Termites are pests that attack planted sugarcane setts, damaging the roots and canes, and can lead to plant death.

Early Shoot-Borer
Early shoot-borer is a pest that affects sugarcane, causing dead-hearts and is most active from April to August.

Internode Borer
Internode borer is a caterpillar pest active from July until harvest, damaging the growing points of sugarcane plants.

Red Rot
Red rot is a fungal disease affecting sugarcane, characterized by symptoms appearing when the crop is about six months old.

Whip Smut
Whip smut is a fungal disease that appears from one month old to harvest, leading to excessive tillering and producing a black whip-like structure.

Grassy Shoot Disease
Grassy shoot disease is caused by a Mycoplasma-like organism, resulting in stunted growth and yellowing of leaves.

Control Measures
Control measures encompass various strategies employed to mitigate pest attacks and diseases in sugarcane cultivation.

Sugarcane Planting and Care Techniques
The techniques include irrigation management, hoeings, tying of canes, and pest and disease control to ensure healthy growth of sugarcane.

Final Earthing-Up
Final earthing-up is a crucial agricultural practice that should be completed before the monsoon rains and generally coincides with the final dose of fertilizer application to manage weeds.

Hoeings and Weedings
Hoeings and weedings refer to the agricultural practices performed to manage weeds during the initial growth stages of crops.

Cane Tying
Cane tying is the practice of securing sugarcane stalks to prevent them from swaying or lodging during windy conditions.

Crop Rotation
Crop rotation is an agricultural practice that involves alternating the types of crops grown in a particular area to improve soil health and manage pests.

Hand Sugar Refractometer
The hand sugar refractometer is a device used to assess the maturity of sugarcane by measuring the sugar content in the stalk.

Small Mill Test (SMT)
The Small Mill Test is a method for analyzing the maturity status of sugarcane by crushing a sample and assessing various quality metrics.

Bamboos
Bamboos are used as props to support sugarcane stalks in some agricultural practices to prevent them from bending or breaking during winds.

Cooperative
The Cooperative is involved in the sugarcane harvesting process, coordinating with farmers for cutting orders based on planting dates and maturity status of the cane.

Sugarcane Harvest
The Sugarcane Harvest is a seasonal event that begins around November and lasts for approximately 150 days, during which sugarcane is harvested and processed.

Laboratory
The laboratory is where samples of sugarcane are analyzed for metrics like poll, brix, purity, and ccs%, determining the maturity status of the cane.

Semi-Trailers
Semi-trailers are used for transporting harvested sugarcane from the transfer stations after it has been cut and processed.

Harvesting Unit
Harvesting Unit refers to the equipment and machinery used in the process of harvesting sugarcane, including harvesters and tractors.

Maturity Status
Maturity Status indicates the level of development of the sugarcane plants, which is crucial for determining the timing of the harvest.

Grinding Capacity
Grinding Capacity refers to the amount of sugarcane that the mill can process, which is a key consideration in planning the harvest.
